WEBVTT

00:08.620 --> 00:12.540
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.180 --> 00:33.520
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.160 --> 00:37.860
And here are your hosts.

00:42.040 --> 00:49.600
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Donald A. Wollheim is one of the versatile
talents that science fiction occasionally produces. He's an author, editor,

00:49.800 --> 00:56.620
critic, and publisher of science fiction. And his influence on the field has
been immense. He became involved in science fiction back in the early 30s, and

00:56.620 --> 01:03.960
many of the things he did had not been done before. He and Forrest Ackerman can
be given much of the credit for starting fandom in the 1930s, for instance. And

01:03.960 --> 01:12.200
as an editor, he's been an innovator and creator many times over. In 1972,
Wollheim founded DAW Books, the first mass-market publishing house devoted

01:12.200 --> 01:20.020
entirely to science fiction. The word DAW, of course, comes from the initials of
Donald A. Wollheim's name. When we spoke with Wollheim, we asked him if he would

01:20.020 --> 01:29.220
tell us about the beginning of DAW Books. Well, you know, I had been with Ace
Books for 19 and a half years. In fact, I was responsible for the founding of

01:29.220 --> 01:39.900
the company, though I didn't own it. And after the death of A. A. Wyn, who was
his original publisher and owner, it passed into the hands of a group of Wall

01:39.900 --> 01:51.000
Street speculators who wanted to build up some kind of a conglomerate in the
communications industry. And unfortunately, they made a number of bad mistakes.

01:51.320 --> 02:02.740
And in about three years, the company was run downhill to where they were in
rather bad financial straits. And it was at that point, when it looked as if we

02:02.740 --> 02:11.640
were likely to have our doors closed at any minute or any day, that I got
together and we talked, you know, I was thinking of the chance to get out and

02:11.640 --> 02:19.900
start my own line. And the man who was the printer for Ace Books came to me and
said, You know, this is getting ridiculous. They owed him months and months of

02:19.900 --> 02:30.160
payment. He said, why don't we break loose and start our own company? Well,
actually, that's put the idea in my head. But I didn't go into partnership with

02:30.160 --> 02:43.740
him. What I did is scout around and we were able to successfully leave Ace and
launch our own company under our name, DAW Books, which is based on my initials.

02:44.420 --> 02:53.640
Wollheim actually neither prints or markets his books. We made a very fine
arrangement with the New American Library that publishes the Signet Books for

02:53.640 --> 03:04.720
distribution and for co-partnership, which means that, in a sense, I feed into
their operations. I am my own editor, my own publisher. I'm an independent

03:04.720 --> 03:14.180
corporation. But they do our printing, they do our marketing and distribution
and handle the minor details. And, of course, we pay them for this. But it's

03:14.180 --> 03:23.200
been a very profitable partnership between us. Wollheim's wife, Elsie, helps him
run DAW Books, so it's sort of a family affair. The odd thing about that was

03:23.200 --> 03:33.740
that originally my secretary from Ace Books was going to come over with me. But
she got a little panicky and was afraid to leave an established job for one

03:33.740 --> 03:44.340
which was insecure, and she didn't come. Instead, my wife, who had, many years
ago before she married me, been president of her own small corporation in the

03:44.340 --> 03:54.720
manufacturing jewelry industry, knew the odds and ends of bookkeeping and
management of her business, instead, you know, came with me. So she's working as

03:54.720 --> 04:03.420
my executive vice president. It's worked out marvelously. We're a husband and
wife team that is really becoming one of the wonders of the industry. We asked

04:03.420 --> 04:13.920
Wollheim how many books he puts out each year. We do four new titles a month,
plus one full reissue of an old title that is sold well and is going out of

04:13.920 --> 04:26.660
stock. That means five releases, actually. But as far as new titles are
concerned, we do approximately 60. That may be novels, reprints of hardcover

04:26.660 --> 04:38.960
books, or new editions of books that have been sold out from other publishers
and are now available again, or anthologies, or some of our annuals. We do

04:38.960 --> 04:49.760
several annuals, the Year's Best Horror, Year's Best Fantasy, and my own annual
World's Best Science Fiction collections. That's always been one of our

04:49.760 --> 04:52.720
mainstays. More with Donald A. Wollheim next time.

04:59.560 --> 05:07.540
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show. A production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:07.540 --> 05:08.280
Odessa, Texas.

