06:01.740 --> 06:05.660
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:21.320 --> 06:26.660
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:29.500 --> 06:31.020
And here are your hosts.

06:34.880 --> 06:42.480
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. We're talking with Donald A. Wollheim,
science fiction author, editor, and presently the publisher of DAW Science

06:42.480 --> 06:50.760
Fiction Books. DAW Books is the only mass publisher devoted entirely to science
fiction, and the company puts out some 60 titles each year. We asked Wollheim how

06:50.760 --> 07:00.960
he selects the books he'll publish. Is there a certain kind of story he looks
for? Well, actually, we try to be as varied as possible, but I go on the premise

07:00.960 --> 07:11.740
in which I've always operated as an editor. If I like it, I publish it. This is
something which I sort of developed over the years. I've been almost 40 years as

07:11.740 --> 07:22.280
an editor. And I discovered that by good luck or bad luck or whatever you have
it, I seem to be, what I like seems to be liked by at least 75% of the potential

07:22.280 --> 07:30.780
readers. So maybe I have good taste, maybe I have bad taste. I don't honestly
know, but all I know is that what I like, I will find that my readers will

07:30.780 --> 07:44.540
generally like. So in science fiction, I like some good hardcore science
fiction. I also like good adventure, the sort of Edgar Rice Burroughs type. We

07:44.540 --> 07:56.900
do a series like that by Dray Prescott. And I like fantasy if it's nicely done.
And I'm really quite, quite wide open in my taste.

08:06.840 --> 08:14.200
Wollheim is noted as an editor and publisher who can spot new talent. In his over
40 years as an editor, he's been responsible for introducing many of today's big

08:14.200 --> 08:21.280
-name writers to the field. Two of his fortunate finds at DAW Books have been C.
 J. Cherryh and Tanith Lee, both of whom published their first novels for

08:21.280 --> 08:31.800
Wollheim. We asked him how he locates writers of that caliber. Do they seek him
out, or does he go looking for them? Both ways, actually. We have an established

08:31.800 --> 08:38.980
image. People know what DAW Books are like. They know what they can expect. We
have a lot of people who are faithful readers because they feel that almost

08:38.980 --> 08:47.780
every book that they buy, regardless of who writes it, is going to be something
they like because their tastes are obviously similar to mine. We pride ourselves

08:47.780 --> 08:56.780
of being one of the very, very few companies that actually looks at and reads
every unsolicited manuscript that comes in. We don't read it all the way

08:56.780 --> 09:05.160
through, but we look at it. Nothing goes through here without being inspected
and read, if it's possible. Now, that's how we find new authors. We found C. J.

09:05.300 --> 09:17.620
Cherryh there. We found Tanith Lee that way. We found many other authors, Michael
Foster and Doris Berserky and so on, Jo Clayton. They are people we found. But

09:17.620 --> 09:24.340
they submitted to us in the first place because they thought we were the kind of
publisher that was doing the kind of book they were writing. And if we both

09:24.340 --> 09:25.820
agree, they're great.

09:33.080 --> 09:43.140
We asked Wollheim if he ever suggests changes in an author's manuscript before
he'll publish it. In a few instances, we will suggest changes, but I don't

09:43.140 --> 09:54.160
really like that system. I pride myself on the fact that the people who become
more or less regular contributors have gotten to know what I like, and what I

09:54.160 --> 10:04.280
like is usually what they like. So we have a situation where I don't have to
tell many authors to rewrite or anything like that. If it's a project, of

10:04.280 --> 10:14.160
course, we'll discuss the possible turns of it before the thing is even written.
But if it's a complete manuscript and I've read it and I like it, great. I do

10:14.160 --> 10:24.480
very little, actually, in that sense of making an author revise and revise. What
about suggesting to an author that he write a sequel or expand a novel into a

10:24.480 --> 10:35.580
trilogy? I usually do not. This is something that authors themselves come up
with. Authors dream of trilogies, and they will submit the first novel

10:35.580 --> 10:43.740
and say there are two more sequels. If I agree with it, I don't mind. We'll
continue our conversation with Donald A. Wollheim on our next show.

10:50.520 --> 10:58.360
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:58.360 --> 10:59.100
Odessa, Texas.

