11:45.680 --> 11:49.600
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:05.280 --> 12:10.600
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:13.260 --> 12:14.940
And here are your hosts.

12:19.120 --> 12:25.800
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Have you ever wondered what goes into the
making of the science fiction paperback you just bought? You know that somebody

12:25.800 --> 12:33.380
wrote it, and that some business enterprise printed it, but you probably don't
think much beyond those general facts. It takes eight months, usually, for the

12:33.380 --> 12:41.580
typical paperback to complete the publishing cycle, and a lot happens in that
time. When we spoke with Donald A. Wollheim, a pioneer fan, author, and editor of

12:41.580 --> 12:48.860
science fiction, and now the publisher of DAW Science Fiction Books, we asked
him if he would trace the publishing process through for us, beginning at the

12:48.860 --> 12:59.520
moment he receives a manuscript. Well, of course. As I said, I have a schedule
of eight months ahead. Now, at the point that I write the manuscript, what I do

12:59.520 --> 13:08.840
then is contact the author or the author's agent, whoever submitted it, and
discuss contract, and then we'll make up the contract which we sent to the

13:08.840 --> 13:19.000
author to be signed. We'll pay out the initial advance on that, and that will
take about anywhere from three weeks to a month, and we put it in our inventory.

13:19.580 --> 13:30.740
The next step is selecting an artist for the cover. Wollheim has an interesting
method for that. If the book is on schedule, within about, well, let's say,

13:31.400 --> 13:42.620
within about two months or three months, I will take the manuscript, and have it
copied, have it Xeroxed, and give a copy to an artist that I think would do the

13:42.620 --> 13:53.180
cover, the right cover for it. A number of different cover artists, and some do
better at certain types of stories than others. I prefer my artists to read the

13:53.180 --> 14:01.540
manuscript. I prefer them to be actually science fiction readers to enjoy the
subject, and they usually do. So if they get a cover, they get a manuscript,

14:01.980 --> 14:10.040
they will then have approximately one month to turn in the finished cover. What
they will do is read it, and then they will sketch out some possible covers,

14:10.180 --> 14:21.180
bring in the sketches. We will okay one of them on guest changes, and they will
have another couple of weeks to turn in the complete painting, which would be

14:21.180 --> 14:30.220
available at the end of that month. At that same time, we would then have to do
and put together the copy for the cover, the material on the back cover, the

14:30.220 --> 14:42.920
titles and all that, which goes out to an agency that
does the layouts and type and all that. Then comes the important job of reading

14:42.920 --> 14:53.340
the manuscript to locate and correct errors. Meanwhile, we then have a month in
which the book must be copy edited. That goes to an editor who goes over the

14:53.340 --> 15:03.540
manuscript, making corrections, correcting spelling, correcting punctuation,
making any minor changes that might be necessary. And I say minor because any

15:03.540 --> 15:15.180
major change would be done by the author, never by the copy editor. So a month
later, that manuscript would then go out to production.

15:16.740 --> 15:25.100
Production, as a man, this would go through the American Library, you
understand. But there's a man there who was an old friend of mine who worked for

15:25.100 --> 15:35.420
me at Ace and who's working for the New American Library now. He will design the
book. He will determine the size type, the layout of the title page, the layout

15:35.420 --> 15:50.600
of pages, and will send it off to the printers. And we will next see in about
anywhere from two to five weeks the galleys and proofs of the front. And by

15:50.600 --> 16:03.480
that time, it would be out a month ago. And the next thing we saw after that
would be the book itself. This just stretches out. So we're about five months

16:03.480 --> 16:14.020
involved in the actual production. But it's a leisurely pace. It stretches out.
It works in very mechanically. And it just runs along. The paperback finally

16:14.020 --> 16:21.260
shows up in a bookstore or supermarket, of course. And in the case of DAW Books,
it will be noticeable. That's because all DAW Books have bright yellow spines,

16:21.440 --> 16:28.740
so they'll stand out in the science fiction section of the bookstore. And a lot
of intricate professional work lies behind that spine. We'll talk again with Donald

16:28.740 --> 16:29.940
A. Wollheim on our next show.

16:37.000 --> 16:44.800
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:44.800 --> 16:51.400
Odessa, Texas. 

