17:59.340 --> 18:01.060
And here are your hosts.

18:05.060 --> 18:13.420
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Since its inception in 1972, DAW Books has
published some of the best science fiction being written today. For the founder

18:13.420 --> 18:20.700
of DAW Books, Donald A. Wollheim, it's been a satisfying and successful venture.
So successful, in fact, that some people have wondered why DAW Books doesn't try

18:20.700 --> 18:30.260
hardback books in addition to the paperbacks it exclusively publishes. Wollheim
tells us why not. There are a couple of reasons for that. For one thing, I don't

18:30.260 --> 18:46.600
know the hardback field. I have, well, I've been an editor of pulp magazines and
of paperback books, newsstand distributed books, since 1941. The New York Times

18:46.600 --> 18:54.700
called me the dean of paperback editors. But to be frank, I have never been an
editor of hardcover books. It's a somewhat different field. The marketing

18:54.700 --> 19:04.200
situation is different. The pricing situation is different. I would be sort of
an amateur. And I don't believe in sticking my neck out into a field in which I

19:04.200 --> 19:14.600
really don't know what I'm doing. Now, I could, of course, make an arrangement
with a hardcover publisher. But I don't see it. I don't believe that a hardcover

19:14.600 --> 19:26.000
book sells that well. You print, well, after all, in paperback, you print by the
tens of thousands of copies. In hardcover, you print what? 3,000 copies? 5,000?

19:26.100 --> 19:34.720
Perhaps 7,000? So a hardcover editor comes in and says, gee, I've got a great
item. It sells 4,000 copies. Well, that's a joke to me. All right, there's money

19:34.720 --> 19:46.340
in it. But I don't need the headache. I don't want it. I don't see it. Other
companies apparently do these things successfully. But that's because they're

19:46.340 --> 19:54.080
probably connected up with a hardcover publisher, people who know their
business. I simply don't feel that I wish to get involved.

20:04.440 --> 20:13.300
We asked Wollheim how many copies a paperback science fiction book would have to
sell before it generated a reasonable profit? That is very difficult to answer

20:13.300 --> 20:24.540
because it would depend on the size of the book and the price of the book. But
very roughly, the average non-bestseller, say, book in the science fiction

20:24.540 --> 20:35.740
fantasy category, may do well at 30,000 copies. In other words, by that point,
it will have cleared its course and made a small profit. Obviously, if it makes

20:35.740 --> 20:50.000
50,000, not 60,000, 75,000 or 100,000, it's great. But the margin is quite low,
surprisingly enough. And so it is not as risky as you may think. Finally,

20:50.240 --> 20:56.940
something of concern to all readers, what about the escalating prices of
paperbacks? How long before high prices make a real difference and begin to hurt

20:56.940 --> 21:05.460
readers? I think it does make a difference. It hasn't affected science fiction,
I think, because we have a very ardent audience. And in general, paperbacks are

21:05.460 --> 21:14.140
holding up much better than most of the book industry. But it does make a
difference. The question of how far prices can go up is something I couldn't

21:14.140 --> 21:24.180
answer you because this is, you know, economic speculation. Who in heck knows? I
mean, nobody, nobody can guess what the economy is. We all hope that the

21:24.180 --> 21:33.660
inflation will stop. And maybe it will. But if it doesn't, why, prices have to
go up accordingly because of the cost of paper, the cost of printers, the cost

21:33.660 --> 21:41.760
of binding, the cost of distribution, the cost of marketing, everything goes up.
And you've got to, you've got to raise your price accordingly or you're, it's

21:41.760 --> 21:52.440
impossible to do business. We do try very hard to be conservative about pricing.
We try to hold it back. We have discussions pretty regularly. I will sometimes

21:52.440 --> 22:00.220
suggest that a book should be, let us say, $2.50. And we'll have the head of
marketing will come in and say, can't you make it $2.25 because you'd like to

22:00.220 --> 22:09.820
hold this down? And if it's practical, we will. If it's not practical, I can't.
But the truth is that nobody wants to raise these prices. But we, you know, you

22:09.820 --> 22:16.440
get pressed. Like anybody in any industry. We'll conclude our discussion with
Donald A. Wollheim on our next show.

