23:55.580 --> 24:04.040
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. DAW Books, publishing some of today's most
popular authors. We asked Donald A. Wollheim, founder and editor of DAW Books,

24:04.220 --> 24:17.360
whose best-selling authors are. Well, our best-sellers are the John Norman Gor
books, Andre Norton's novels, C. J. Cherryh does very nicely, Tanith Lee goes

24:17.360 --> 24:31.680
back to press pretty continuously, and let's see, well, we have quite a number
that do very nicely. Marion Zimmer Bradley, for instance, is always short, kept

24:31.680 --> 24:43.420
continuously in print. We do the Mike Moorcock books, and they're continuously
in print. We do, well, many titles of that sort. So, our best-seller is John

24:43.420 --> 24:54.920
Norman, of course. He sells by half a million at a book, and constantly in
print. In addition to books by individual authors, DAW Books also publishes many

24:54.920 --> 25:04.000
anthologies each year. The best-known as DAW's annual The World's Best Science
Fiction, published each year since DAW Books' inception in 1972. We asked

25:04.000 --> 25:14.600
Wollheim if he selected the stories in his anthologies himself. Uh, yes. It's a
tough cure, and I work with Arthur Saha, who is an old-time science fiction fan

25:14.600 --> 25:24.720
and a determined reader of everything that comes out. And so Saha does the first
reading and sorts out the junk from the good ones and gives me a list of what he

25:24.720 --> 25:36.760
thinks I should read. Well, that saves me an awful lot of work, and I sort
through his recommended list, and finally, we arrive at a, what we consider the

25:36.760 --> 25:49.120
ten best, and that creates our annual. Does he have any criteria he goes by?
Yeah, if I like the story. Basically, of course, it also is the originality of

25:49.120 --> 25:59.500
concept and originality of plot, and of course, how well it's written. All these
factors come into play. Generally speaking, if it's got a really original idea,

25:59.900 --> 26:08.960
I would be strongly in favor of it. Unfortunately, science fiction being what it
is, not too many will come up with original ideas these days. We asked Wollheim

26:08.960 --> 26:20.640
to tell us about some of the other anthologies DAW Books puts out, and we also
asked if his anthologies sold well. For us, they sell quite well. We have no

26:20.640 --> 26:31.960
problems with the annual. We reissue it, usually four years later, as Wollheim's
World's Best Series five or four or six, because you can't have a dated book. A

26:31.960 --> 26:44.320
dated book prejudices your dealers. So our 1982 annual, which is coming out in a
couple of months, of course, covers the best in 1981. Other books, like the

26:44.320 --> 26:57.020
Year's Best Horror Stories, being edited for us by Karl Edward Wagner, who is
himself a good name and a good writer in that field. Year's Best Fantasy, used

26:57.020 --> 27:01.440
to be edited for us by Lin Carter, but now is being handled by Arthur Saha
directly.

27:04.460 --> 27:17.420
And Isaac Asimov is doing an encyclopedic study of the early days, beginning
with 1939 and working up to the present in about two books a year, called Asimov

27:17.420 --> 27:30.980
Presents the Great SF Stories. And I did one volume of Terra SF, which was the
best stories from Western Europe, which was edited for me by a French science

27:30.980 --> 27:40.960
fiction fan that's familiar with the field and managed to arrange to get
translations from all over Western Europe. I will probably continue that on a

27:40.960 --> 27:51.640
once-every-two-years basis. So it works. Wollheim has had a career in science
fiction that's lasted over 50 years. In all aspects of science fiction, he's one

27:51.640 --> 27:59.840
of the pioneers of the field. He's been a fan, an author, a critic, an editor,
and now, with DAW Books, a publisher. As with few others, he's devoted his life

27:59.840 --> 28:02.540
to science fiction and left an indelible mark on the field.

